<div class="s2"><h1>A Mathematical Theory for the Spread of Computer Viruses</h1><p><a href="/lib/?lang=en&amp;author=Gleissner%2C%20Winfried">Winfried Gleissner</a><br/> <em>Computers & Security, 8, 1989, pp.35-41</em><br/> <em>ISSN 0167-4048</em><br/> <em>February 1989</em></p><script type="text/rocketscript">var disqus_url = 'http://vxheaven.org/lib/mwg02.html';</script><div class="ci"><a href="/lib/?ci=mwg02">10</a></div><img src="/img/pdf.gif" alt="PDF"/><a href="/lib/pdf/A%20Mathematical%20Theory%20for%20the%20Spread%20of%20Computer%20Viruses.pdf">Download</a> PDF (400.13Kb) (You need to be registered on <a href="/forum">forum</a>)<br/>[<a style="" href="/lib/?lang=EN&amp;index=TH#mwg02">Back to index</a>] [<a href="/lib/mwg02.html#disqus_thread">Comments</a>]<br/><h2>Abstract</h2><p>A model is introduced to treat the spread of computer viruses mathematically. A recurrence formula is given which allows a closed expression to be derived for the probability that, starting from an initial state, a given viral state will be reached after executing exactly <em>k</em> programs. In some special cases this recurrence formula can be used for numeric computations, It is shown that the infection process does not stop before all programs are infected, which are visible for any infected program in the initial state.</p><p>[<a href="/lib/mwg02.html">Read the article</a>]</p></div>
